metadata.difficulty_analysis:
Compared with the original two–dimensional problem about a single parabola tangent to the coordinate axes, the present variant

• raises the dimension from ℝ² to ℝ³ and deals with a full quadric surface (ten independent coefficients) instead of a conic (six coefficients);  
• introduces six simultaneous geometric conditions, four of which involve higher-order tangency or containment;  
• requires classification of the quadric via eigenvalue analysis of a 3×3 symmetric matrix;  
• demands mastery of rigid motions (rotations and translations) in 3-space to bring the quadric to canonical form;  
• asks for the 3-D analogues of focus and directrix and for a non-trivial volume computation;  
• necessitates the coordination of algebraic, differential-geometric and multivariable-calculus techniques.

Each of these items is absent from the original exercise and substantially increases both conceptual and computational complexity, thereby meeting the requirement that the enhanced kernel variant be significantly harder.

